<BODY><!-- Heading -->
<DIV id=3Dheader>
<H1><A href=3D"http://www.robweir.com/blog/">An Antic Disposition =
</A></H1>
<P id=3Ddescription>Rob Weir, thinking the unthinkable, pondering the=20
imponderable, effing the ineffable and scruting the =
inscrutable</P></DIV><!-- Main Column -->
<DIV id=3DmainClm><!-- Blog Posts -->
<H3>Monday, March 24, 2008</H3><A name=3D4949663472099773441></A>
<H2>OOXML's (Out of) Control Characters</H2>
<DIV class=3DblogPost>
<DIV style=3D"CLEAR: both"></DIV>Let's start with the concepts of =
=E2=80=9Clexical=E2=80=9D and=20
=E2=80=9Cvalue=E2=80=9D spaces in XML, as well as the mechanism of =
=E2=80=9Cderivation by restriction=E2=80=9D=20
in XML Schema. Any engineer can understand the basics here, even if you =
don't=20
eat and drink XML for breakfast.<BR><BR>The value space for an XML data =
item=20
comprises the set of all allowed values. So the value space for the =
=E2=80=9Cfloat=E2=80=9D data=20
type would be all floating point numbers, such as <B>12.34</B> or =
<B>43.21</B>.=20
The lexical space comprises all ways of expressing these values in the =
character=20
stream of an XML document. So lexical representations of the value =
<B>12.34</B>=20
include =E2=80=9C12.34=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9C12.340=E2=80=9D and =
'1.234E1=E2=80=9D. For ease of illustration I will=20
indicate value space items in bold, and lexical space items in quotes. =
In=20
general there are multiple lexical representations that may represent =
the same=20
value.<BR><BR>Character data in XML also permits more than one lexical=20
representation of the same value. For example, =E2=80=9CA=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9C&amp;#65;=E2=80=9D both=20
represent the value <SPAN style=3D"FONT-WEIGHT: bold">A</SPAN>. The =
=E2=80=9Cnumerical=20
character reference=E2=80=9D approach allows an XML author to easily =
encode the=20
occasional Unicode character which is not part of the author's native =
editing=20
environment, e.g., adding the copyright character or occasional foreign=20
character. The value space allowed by XML includes most of Unicode, =
including=20
all of the major writing systems of the world, current and=20
historical.<BR><BR>The concern I have with DIS 29500 concerns Ecma's=20
introduction of a ST_XString (Escaped String) datatype. This new type is =
defined=20
via the following XML Schema definition:<BR><BR>&lt;simpletype=20
name=3D"ST_Xstring"&gt;<BR>&lt;restriction=20
base=3D"xsd:string"&gt;<BR>&lt;/simpletype&gt;<BR><BR>This uses the =
=E2=80=9Cderivation by=20
restriction=E2=80=9D facility of XML Schema to define a new type, =
derived from the=20
standard xsd:string schema type. The xsd:string type is defined to allow =
only=20
character values that are also allowed in the XML standard.<BR><BR>The =
use of=20
derivation by restriction implies a clear relationship between the =
ST_Xstring=20
type and the base type xsd:string. This is stated in XML Schema Part 1, =
<A=20
href=3D"http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#Type_Definition_Summary">clause=
=20
2.2.1.1</A>:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BR>A type definition whose declarations or facets are in a=20
  one-to-one relation with those of another specified type definition, =
with each=20
  in turn restricting the possibilities of the one it corresponds to, is =
said to=20
  be a <B>restriction</B>.<BR><BR>The specific restrictions might =
include=20
  narrowed ranges or reduced alternatives. Members of a type, A, whose=20
  definition is a restriction of the definition of another type, B, are =
always=20
  members of type B as well.<BR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>The latest sentence can =
be taken=20
as a restatement of the <A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liskov_substitution_principle">Lisko=
v=20
Substitution Principle</A>, a fundamental principle of interface design, =
that a=20
subtype should be usable (substitutable) wherever a base type is usable. =
It is=20
this principle that ensures interoperability. A type derived by =
restriction=20
limits, restricts, constrains, reduces the permitted value space of its =
base=20
type, but it cannot increase the value space beyond that permitted by =
its base=20
type.<BR><BR>So, with that background, let's now look at how OOXML =
defines the=20
semantics of its ST_Xstring type:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BR>ST_Xstring (Escaped String)<BR><BR>String of characters =
with=20
  support for escaped invalid-XML characters.<BR><BR>For all characters =
which=20
  cannot be represented in XML as defined by the XML 1.0 specification, =
the=20
  characters are escaped using the Unicode numerical character =
representation=20
  escape character format _xHHHH_, where H represents a hexadecimal =
character in=20
  the character's value. [Example: The Unicode character 8 is invalid in =
an XML=20
  1.0 document, so it shall be escaped as _x0008_. end =
example]<BR><BR>This=20
  simple type's contents are a restriction of the XML Schema string=20
datatype.<BR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>In other words, although ST_Xstring is =
declared to=20
be a restriction of xsd:string it is, via a proprietary escape notation, =
in fact=20
expanding the semantics of xsd:string to create a value space that =
includes=20
additional characters, including characters that are invalid in=20
XML.<BR><BR>Let's review some of the problems it =
introduces.<BR><BR>First, the=20
semantics of XML strings that contain invalid XML-characters is =
undefined by=20
this or any other standard. For example, OOXML uses ST_Xstring in Part =
4, Clause=20
3.3.1.30 to store the error message which should be displayed when a =
data=20
validation formula fails. But what should an OOXML-supporting =
application do=20
when given a display string which contains control characters from the =
C0=20
control range, characters forbidden in XML 1.0?<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>U+0004 END OF TRANSMISSION<BR>
  <LI>U+0006 ACKNOWLEDGE
  <LI>U+0007 BELL<BR>
  <LI>U+0008 BACKSPACE
  <LI>U+0017 SYNCHRONOUS IDLE<BR></LI></UL>How should these characters =
be=20
displayed?<BR><BR>There is a reason XML excludes these dumb terminal =
control=20
codes. They are neither desired nor necessary in XML.<BR><BR>Elliotte =
Rusty=20
Harold explains the rationale for this prohibition in his book <A=20
href=3D"http://www.cafeconleche.org/books/effectivexml/"><I>Effective=20
XML</I></A>:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BR>The first 32 Unicode characters with code points 0 to 31 =
are=20
  known as the C0 controls. They were originally defined in ASCII to =
control=20
  teletypes and other monospace dumb terminals. Aside from the tab, =
carriage=20
  return, and line feed they have no obvious meaning in text. Since XML =
is text,=20
  it does not include binary characters such as NULL (#x00), BEL (#x07), =
DC1=20
  (#x11) through DC4 (#x14), and so forth. These noncharacters are =
historic=20
  relics. XML 1.0 does not allow them.<BR><BR><!-- Is it really hasty or =
nasty? -->This is a good thing.=20
  Although dumb terminals and binary-hostile gateways are far less =
common today=20
  than they were twenty years ago, they are still used, and passing =
these=20
  characters through equipment that expects to see plain text can have =
nasty=20
  consequences, including disabling the =
screen.<BR></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Further, since=20
these characters are undefined in XML, they are unlikely to work well =
with=20
existing accessibility interfaces and devices. At best these characters =
will be=20
ignored and introduce subtle errors. For example, what does =
=E2=80=9C$10,[BS]000=E2=80=9D become=20
if one system processes the backspace and another does not? Worst case, =
the=20
accessibility interface expecting a certain range of characters as =
defined by=20
the xsd:string type will crash when presented with values beyond the =
expected=20
range.<BR><BR>Interfaces with existing programming languages are also =
harmed by=20
ST_Xstring. How does a C or C++ XML parser deal with XML that now can =
allow a=20
U+0000 (NULL) character in the middle of a string, something which is =
illegal in=20
that programming language?<BR><BR>What about XML database interfaces =
that take=20
XML data and store it in relational tables? If they are schema-aware and =
see=20
that ST_Xstring is merely a restriction of xsd:string, they will assume =
the=20
normal range of characters can be stored wherever an xsd:string can be =
stored.=20
But since the value space is expanded, there is no guarantee that this =
will=20
still be true. These characters may cause validation errors in the=20
database.<BR><BR>By now, the observant reader may be accusing me of =
pulling a=20
fast one. "But Rob, none of the above is a problem if the application =
simply=20
leaves the ST_Xstring encoded and does not try to decode or interpret =
the=20
non-XML character," you might say.<BR><BR>OK. Fair enough. Let's follow =
that=20
approach and see where it leads us.<BR><BR>Let's look at =
interoperability with=20
other XML-based standards. Imagine you do a DOM parse of an OOXML =
document that=20
contains =E2=80=9Cstrings=E2=80=9D of type ST_Xstring. Either your =
parser/application is=20
OOXML-aware, or it isn't. In other words, either it is able to interpret =
the=20
non-standard _xHHHH_ instructions, or it isn't.<BR><BR>If it doesn't =
understand=20
them, then any other code that operates on the DOM nodes with ST_Xstring =
data is=20
at risk of returning the wrong answer. For example, what is the length =
of the=20
string =E2=80=9CABC=E2=80=9D? Three-characters, of course. But what is =
the length of the string=20
=E2=80=9C_x0041_BC=E2=80=9D ? These two strings both have the same =
values according to OOXML.=20
But an XML application might return 9 or return 3, depending on whether =
it is=20
OOXML-aware or not. Since most (all) XML parsers are unaware of the =
non-standard=20
escape mechanism proposed by OOXML, they will typically calculate things =
such as=20
string lengths, string comparisons, string sorting, etc.,=20
incorrectly.<BR><BR>But suppose the parser/application is OOXML-aware =
and=20
correctly decodes these character references into the correct Unicode =
values,=20
then what? Assuming the host language doesn't crash from the existence =
of this=20
control characters, we then are presented with problems at the interface =
with=20
any other code that operates on the DOM. Suppose we try to transform the =
DOM via=20
XSLT to XHTML. Will the XSLT engine properly handle the existence of =
these=20
forbidden character values? The XSLT engine may just crash. But suppose =
it=20
doesn't. How does it write out these control characters into XHTML? It =
can't.=20
These values are not permitted in XHTML. Dead end. What about DocBook? =
DITA?=20
OpenDocument Format? Not possible. Since these characters are not =
permitted in=20
XML 1.0 at all, they will be forbidden in all other markup languages =
that are=20
based on XML 1.0, or even XML 1.1 for that matter (XML 1.1 allows some =
but not=20
all of these characters, in particular the NULL character is=20
excluded).<BR><BR>Note further that with XML pipelining and with =
mashups, the=20
application that writes XML output typically does not have direct =
knowledge of=20
the application that originally produced the XML values. This decoupling =
of=20
producers and consumers is an essential aspect of modern systems =
integration,=20
include Web Services. By corrupting XML string values in the way that it =
does,=20
DIS 29500 breaks the ability to have loosely coupled systems. Once the =
value=20
space is polluted by these aberrant control characters, every =
application, every=20
process that touches this data must be aware of their non-standard=20
idiosyncrasies lest they crash or return incorrect answers. In this way, =
one=20
standard perverts the entire XML universe, forcing them all to contend =
with the=20
poor hygiene of a single vendor.<BR><BR>The reader might think that I =
exaggerate=20
the importance of this, that surely ST_Xstring is only used in OOXML in =
edge=20
cases, in rare, compatibility modes. We wish that this were true. =
However, a=20
look at the DIS 29500 shows that ST_Xstring is pervasive, and in fact is =
the=20
predominant data type in SpreadsheetML, used to express the vast =
majority of=20
spreadsheet content, including cell contents, headers, footers, displays =

strings, error strings, tooltip help, range names, etc. Any application =
that=20
operates on an OOXML spreadsheet will need to deal with this =
mess.<BR><BR>For=20
example, here are some uses of ST_Xstring in DIS 29500, Part 4:<BR>
<UL>
  <LI>Clause 3.2.3 for the name of a custom view in a spreadsheet<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.2.5 for the name of a spreadsheet named range, for the=20
  descriptive comment, for the name description, for the<BR>help topic, =
the=20
  keyboard shortcut, the status bar text and for the menu item text<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.2.14 for the name of a spreadsheet function group<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.2.19 for the name of a sheet in a workbook<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.2.22 for the name of a smart tag as well as for the URL =
of a=20
  smart tag.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.2.25 for the destination file name and title when =
publishing=20
  spreadsheet to the web.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.10 for the value of a conditional formatting object, =
e.g., a=20
  gradient<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.20 for the name of a custom property<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.28 for sheet and range names<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.30 for error message string, error message title, =
prompt=20
  string and prompt title in a spreadsheet data validation =
definition.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.35 for the value of a footer for even numbered =
pages.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.36 for the value of a header for even numbered =
pages.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.38 for the content of the first page footer<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.39 for the content of the first page header<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.44 for the display string for a hyperlink, the =
tooltip help=20
  for the link, also the anchor target if the hyperlink is to an HTML =
page<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.49 for values of input cells in a scenario<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.50 for cell inline text values<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.55 for the value of a footer for odd numbered =
pages.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.56 for the value of a header for odd numbered =
pages.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.73, in scenarios for the comment text, the scenario =
name and=20
  the name of the person who last changed the scenario.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.88 when defining sort condition, for the values of a =
the=20
  custom sort list<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.93 for the value contained within a cell<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.1.94 for information associated with items published to =
the=20
  web, including the destination file and the title of the output HTML =
file<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.2.2 for expressing the criteria values in a filter<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.3.15 for the key/values for smart tag properties<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.4.4 for expressing the contents of a rich text run<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.4.5 for expressing the name of a font<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.4.6 for expressing the text of a phonetic hint for East =
Asian=20
  text<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.4.8 for expressing a text item in the shared string =
table<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.4.12 for the text content shown as part of a string<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.5.1.2 for a table, expressing a textual comment, a =
display name=20
  as well as style names.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.5.1.3 for a table column, expressing cell and row style =
names,=20
  column name<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.5.1.7 for column properties created from an XML mapping, =
for=20
  expressing the associated XPath.<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.5.2.4 for the XPath associated with column properties for =
XML=20
  tables<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.7.1-3.7.6 for specifying content of tracked comments, =
including=20
  the text of the comments as well as the authors of the comments<BR>
  <LI>Clause 3.8.29 expressing the name of a font<BR><BR></LI></UL>There =
are=20
hundreds of additional uses. A search of DIS 29500 Part 4 for =
=E2=80=9CST_Xstring=E2=80=9D=20
returns 467 hits. OOXML also defines two additional types, =
=E2=80=9Clptsr=E2=80=9D (7.4.2.8) and=20
=E2=80=9Cbstr=E2=80=9D (7.4.2.4) that have the same flaw as =
ST_Xstring.<BR><BR>The reader might=20
further argue that, although the type allows characters that are =
forbidden by=20
XML, the actual occurrence of these values in real legacy documents is =
likely to=20
be rare. This might be true, but this is cause for even greater concern. =
If=20
every document contained these control characters, then we would =
immediately be=20
aware of any interoperability problems when integrating OOXML data with =
other=20
systems. But if these characters are permitted, but occur rarely and =
randomly,=20
then the integration errors will also occur rarely and randomly, =
allowing data=20
corruption and other problems to occur and propagate further before=20
detection.<BR><BR>In summary, we are concerned that the ST_Xstring type =
in OOXML=20
opens us up to problems such as:<BR><BR>
<OL>
  <LI>Introducing accessibility problems<BR>
  <LI>Breaking unaware C/C++ XML parsers<BR>
  <LI>Breaking XML databases<BR>
  <LI>Breaking interoperability with other XML languages
  <LI>Breaking application logic related to string searching, sorting,=20
  comparisons, etc.<BR>
  <LI>Introducing errors that will be hard to detect and=20
resolve<BR><BR></LI></OL>Possible remedies include:<BR>
<OL><BR>
  <LI>Use xsd:string uniformly instead of ST_Xstring, with no use of =
forbidden=20
  XML characters. This would require that applications that read legacy =
binary=20
  documents containing such characters eliminate them at this point, =
perhaps=20
  replacing them with licit characters or with whitespace. No =
application will=20
  be more able to devise the original meaning and intent of these =
characters=20
  than the original vendor. So they should be responsible for cleaning =
up these=20
  strings to make them XML-ready.<BR>
  <LI>Use a non-string type such as the binary xsd:hexBinary or =
xsd:base64Binary=20
  to represent these data items.<BR>
  <LI>Use a mixed content encoding, where the licit characters are =
represented=20
  by xsd:string data, and the forbidden characters are denoted by=20
  specially-defined elements. So =E2=80=9CA_x0008_BC=E2=80=9D would =
become:=20
  &lt;text&gt;A&lt;backspace/&gt;BC &lt;/text&gt;. In this case the =
semantics of=20
  the &lt;backspace&gt; element would need to be documented in the DIS =
29500=20
  specification, including its effect on searching, sorting, length=20
  calculations, etc.</LI></OL>
